@crigor the behavior you're seeing is to be expected.  If a host isn't explicitly removed from the etcd cluster, etcd assumes the node is _temporarily_ unreachable due to network issues or reboot and that it's coming back sooner or later.  And if the cluster already had its max number of peers before one machine went offline and was replaced by autoscaling, the new node does indeed become a proxy.

Expected though it may be, there are some things you can do to combat this behavior.  There are instructions [here](http://docs.deis.io/en/latest/managing_deis/add_remove_host/#automatic-host-removal) on how to have Deis automatically remove a node's membership in the ceph and etcd clusters before reboot, shutdown, or halt events.

Alternatively (advanced) you can isolate etcd to a small, fixed number of nodes as described [here](http://docs.deis.io/en/latest/managing_deis/isolating-etcd/) and [here](https://coreos.com/os/docs/latest/cluster-architectures.html#production-cluster-with-central-services).  When doing this, the intent would be to treat the etcd nodes as "pets" instead of "cattle" and invest in their long-term health instead of allowing them to be replaced by the sort of scaling events that may impact all your other ("cattle") nodes.

