There is indeed a workaround. If ``test_foo()`` is a member function of ``Foo`` then everything works as expected. But this is ugly and not ideal.

C++ code:
```
struct Foo {
	int a = 0;
	Foo() = default;
	Foo(const Foo &) = delete;
	Foo &operator=(const Foo &) = delete;
	Foo(Foo &&o) = delete;
	Foo &operator=(Foo &&o) = delete;
};
py::class_<Foo> foo(m, "Foo");
foo.def("__init__", [](Foo &t) {
	new (&t)Foo();
	});
foo.def_readwrite("a", &Foo::a);
foo.def("test_foo", [](Foo &x, std::function<void(Foo &)> f) {
	f(x);				// x.a = 1
	return x.a;
}, "f"_a);
```

Python code:
```
def test_obj():
    def change_value(x):
        x.a = 1
    x = m.Foo()
    assert x.test_foo(change_value) == 1
```

