To expand on (2), my suggestion is more or less this:

```cpp
// common.h
struct internals {
    ...
    // could be extended with more optional data to be shared across Python modules
    // without breaking base pybind11 API
    std::unordered_map<std::string, void *> capsules;  // could be named `shared_data`
}
```

```cpp
// numpy.h
struct numpy_type_info { ... }

struct numpy_internals {
    std::unordered_map<std::type_index, numpy_type_info> registered_dtypes;
};

...

numpy_internals& get_numpy_internals() {
    // (numpy_internals *) get_internals().capsules["numpy"]
}
```

The extra map in `internals` is to decouple it from other code that wants to share arbitrary data across Python modules using the existing versioned pybind11 capsules.

In the updated backtrace you pasted, the main thread is in the middle of interpreter shutdown, having already dropped its references to the imported modules, and the crashing thread is trying to getattr() on a module object that has already been freed. You can avoid this by changing async_run() to give each thread its own reference to the Python module object, which it drops when it has extracted the necessary attribute:
```
        for (int i = 0; i < 2; i++) {
            for (py::module m : plugins) {
                threads.emplace_back([m, this]() mutable {
                    auto gil = std::make_unique<py::gil_scoped_acquire>();
                    py::object func = m.attr("func");
                    m.release().dec_ref();
                    py::tuple args = py::make_tuple(this);
                    // (remainder is as before)
```
With this change I'm unable to reproduce a segfault.

----

Taking a step back, I think you are trying to do something _exceedingly tricky_ by destroying the plugin_handler (and thus the interpreter) while detached threads are still potentially executing Python code. If you fix all the obvious bugs it's more likely that you'll be left with some lurking non-obvious bugs than that you'll be left with correct code. It would be much safer to devise some mechanism of signaling your threads to exit, and making sure they have all done so before you destroy the plugin_handler.

It turns out that this also is fairly tricky, though, and I wasn't able to get a robustly working example in the time I was willing to spend on it. If you use pthread_cancel() you have to contend with the same stack unwinding issues as pthread_exit() was causing, and if you use PyThreadState_SetAsyncExc() you can only interrupt Python code (e.g. a sleep() will wait until it's done). If you're curious, here's what I did with PyThreadState_SetAsyncExc():
```
        for (int i = 0; i < 2; i++) {
            for (const auto& m : plugins) {
                threads.emplace_back([&m, this]() {
                    try {
                        py::gil_scoped_acquire gil;
                        if (exiting) return;
                        m.attr("func")(this);
                    } catch (py::error_already_set&) {
                        // assume the only way we can get an exception
                        // is the KeyboardInterrupt thrown in by the
                        // plugin_handler destructor -- real code would
                        // have better exception handling
                    }
                });
            }
...
    ~plugin_handler()
    {
        std::cout << "destructing...\n";

        nogil.reset(); // reacquire the GIL to notify the threads
        exiting = true;
        for (auto &t : threads) {
            PyThreadState_SetAsyncExc((long) t.native_handle(), PyExc_KeyboardInterrupt);
        }
        py::gil_scoped_release scope; // release again to let them complete
        for (auto &t : threads) {
            t.join();
        }
    }
...
    std::unique_ptr<py::gil_scoped_release> nogil;
    bool exiting = false; // guarded by the GIL
};
```
Stopping threads safely in a way that works for all threads is much, much harder than it seems like it ought to be. (This is why Python and C++ don't provide native thread cancellation facilities.) It's almost always better to do it at the application level, with something like "send a message telling it to exit".

